 in England. The lessons from the research are used to explore the government’s changes in public health now being implemented, most of which centre on new partnerships called Health and Wellbeing Boards that have been established to work differently from their predecessors.The book assesses their likely impact and the implications for the future of public health partnerships. Drawing on systems thinking, it argues that partnerships can only succeed if they work in quite different ways. The book will therefore appeal to the public health community and students of health policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aInteragency coordinationzGreat Britain. 0aMedical policyzGreat Britain. 0aMedical policy. 0aPublic health administration. 0aPublic healthzGreat Britain. 7aMEDICAL / Epidemiology.2bisacsh1 aHunter, David J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeckham, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerkins, Neil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z9783111196343oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144730131840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447301332423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447301332/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPb2014